'''Mirchpur''' is an [[Indus Valley Civilization]] site and village in [[Narnaund]], [[Hisar (district)|Hissar district]], [[Haryana]], India.

==Demographics of 2011==
As of [[2011 census of India|2011 India census]], Mirchpur had a population of 8737 in 1670 households. Males (4706) constitute 53.85%  of the population and females (4031) 46.13%. Mirchpur has an average literacy (5498) rate of 62.92%, lower than the national average of 74%: male literacy (3464) is 63%, and female literacy (2034) is 36.99% of total literates (5498). In Mirchpur, Hisar 10.91% of the population is under 6&nbsp;years of age (954).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=69290|title=Census of India 2011|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Castes]] constitutes 17.81% of total population village at 1556 out of 8737.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census2011.co.in/data/village/61026-mirchpur-haryana.html|title=Mirchpur Village Population - Narnaund - Hisar, Haryana|website=www.census2011.co.in|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref>

==Indus Valley Civilization Site==
<!--- NOTE: The missing wiki articles in red will be created within next few days. Please do not remove --->
Sisai is an [[Indus Valley Civilization]] site with three mounds Sisai 1, Sisai 2 and Sisai 2.

Bolstering the status of Rakhigarhi as the largest [[Indus Valley Civilization]] metropolis on the banks of [[Drishadvati river]] (current day paleochannel of [[Chautang]]), at least 23 other Indus Valley Civilization sites within 5&nbsp;km (at 4 sites), 10&nbsp;km (at least 10 sites) and 15&nbsp;km (at least 9 sites) radius of Rakhigarhi have been discovered till 2001. Some of the raw materials were procured from the nodal ''Rakhigarhi'' site and finished products were brought back to the nodal ''Rakhigarhi'' site for marketing.<ref name="ASIR1">[http://asi.nic.in/pdf_data/rakhigarhi_excavation_report_new.pdf ASI Rakhigarhi Excavation Report for 1997-98 and 199-2001 excavations, Author: Dr. Amrendra Nath, Publisher: Archaeological Survey of India, Published: 2004]</ref>

Within 5&nbsp;km radius are [[Indus Valley Civilisation#Early Harappan|early Harappan (4600 BCE - 2800 BCE)]] site of [[Gamra]] and [[Indus Valley Civilisation#Mature Harappan|mature Harappan (2600 BCE - 1400 BCE)]] sites of [[Budana]], [[Haibatpur]] and [[Lohari Ragho|Lohari Ragho 3]].<ref name="ASIR1"/>

Within 5&nbsp;km to 10&nbsp;km radius, early Harappan sites are [[Lohari Ragho|Lohari Ragho 1]] [[Lohari Ragho|Lohari Ragho 2]]
and [[Kheri Lochab]]-[[Kheri Jalab]]. Mature Harappan small farmstead sites are [[Milakpur]] and [[Gunkali]]. Small farmstead sites of [[Kinnar, Hisar|Kinnar]], [[Nara, Hisar|Nara]] and Mirchpur have material from both mature and late Harappan period. [[Indus Valley Civilisation#Collapse and Late Harappan|late Harappan (after 1400 BCE)]] sites are [[Sothi|Sotha]] and
[[Khera Gandawala|Gandaswala Khera]].<ref name="ASIR1"/>

Within 5&nbsp;km to 10&nbsp;km radius are early, mature and late Harrpan sites. To the north-west of Rakhigarhi are [[Panihari village|Panhari]], [[Gyanpura]], [[Sothi|Sotha]], [[Kagsar]], [[Sulchani]] and south-west of Rakhigarhi are [[Sisai, Hisar|Sisai 1, 2 and 3]], [[Rajpura, Narnaund|Rajpura 2]], [[Pali, Narnaund|Pali]] and [[Masudpur]].<ref name="ASIR1"/>

==Mirchpur Dalit killings incident==
In 2010, Jai Prakash's house at [[Dalit]] [[Valmiki caste|Valmiki]] community colony of Mirchpur has a 2 year old dog named Ruby, which allegedly barked at some 10 to 15 drunk boys from [[Jat people|Jat]] community drove on motorcycles in front of his house.<ref name="Author 2010">{{cite web | last=Author | first=The | title=Mirchpur: A Dog Story | website=OPEN Magazine | date=2010-05-01 | url=http://www.openthemagazine.com/article/india/mirchpur-a-dog-story | access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://roundtableindia.co.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4686:mirchpur-carnage-against-dalits&catid=122&Itemid=138|title=Mirchpur Carnage Against Dalits|last=kuffir|work=Round Table India|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-gb}}</ref> One of the Jat boys, Rajinder Pali hurled a brick at the dog which was objected by a young dalit boy named Yogesh which lead to physical fight between them.<ref name="Author 2010" /> Jat boys threatened dalits of dire consequences for this.<ref name="Author 2010" /> Later. two Balmiki elders named Veer Bhan and Karan Singh apologized to Jat elders and still got beaten by them.<ref name="Author 2010" /> Narnaund's Station House Officer (SHO) Vinod Kumar Kajal was close to a prominent Jat of Mirchpur.<ref name="Author 2010" /> On 21 April 2010 all Dalit men were invited for a compromise to another place.<ref name="Author 2010" /> In their absence, 300 to 400 Jat men,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/dogs-bark-triggered-mirchpur-dalits-killing-incident/articleshow/65536703.cms|title=Dog's bark triggered Mirchpur Dalits killing incident - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> women came with jerry cans of kerosene and petrol, agricultural implements and lathis first ransacking jewels, cash, clothes in the houses and than setting the homes ablaze with dalit women and kids inside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/mirchpur-violence-case-dalit-residents-pet-dog-barking-at-accused-led-to-dalits-killing-rioting-in-haryana-village-5043101.html|title=Mirchpur violence: Resident's pet dog barking at accused led to Dalits' killing, rioting in Haryana village - Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> This led to [[Death by burning]] of 70-year-old Tara Chand and his 18-year-old physically challenged daughter Suman in fire.<ref name="Author 2010" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/mirchpur-dalit-killing-delhi-hc-convicts-20-more-says-jats-deliberately-attacked-valmiki-community-1855261.html|title=Mirchpur Dalit Killings: Delhi HC Convicts 20 More, Says Jats Attacked 'Deliberately'|work=News18|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> After this incident, 200 dalit families left the village fearing for their safety. Only 50 families remained with a group of 75 [[Central Reserve Police Force|CRPF]] personnel deployed in the village.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/after-delhi-high-court-verdict-abandoned-dalit-homes-tension-in-air-at-mirchpur-5325039/|title=After Delhi High Court verdict: Abandoned Dalit homes, tension in air at Mirchpur|date=2018-08-26|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> Police named 103 people in the charge sheet out of which 5 were juveniles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/mirchpur-dalits-killings-delhi-high-court-dalits-attacked-jat-tara-chand-valmiki-community/274335|title=Mirchpur Dalits killings: Delhi High Court convicts 20, says attack was 'pre-planned'|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> In September 2011, 15 people were convicted and 82 acquitted by a Sessions court.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/15-convicted-82-acquitted-in-Mirchpur-Dalit-murder-case/article13609731.ece|title=15 convicted, 82 acquitted in Mirchpur Dalit murder case|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2011-09-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> CRPF was withdrawn in December 2016. In January 2017, Shiv Kumar a 17-year-old Dalit boy (also a district-level athlete) won a cash prize of Rs 1,500 in the cycle-stunt competition at a local playground.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/let-s-talk-about-hate-dalits-of-mirchpur-left-home-behind-to-escape-caste-oppression/story-hn298fSWvrvTmHzFQa9Z1K.html|title=‘They couldn’t tolerate a Dalit winning’: In Mirchpur, caste oppression divides|date=2017-07-25|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en}}</ref> A group of youths from the upper castes [[Brahmin]]s, [[Lohar]]s, [[Khati]]s<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/in-mirchpur-a-race-leads-to-clashes-many-caste-narratives-dalit-4505066/|title=In Mirchpur, a race leads to clashes, many caste narratives|date=2017-02-03|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> including Jats allegedly passing casteist remarks against him which led to a fight where nine Dalit youths, aged between 14 and 25, were severely injured. After this incident remaining 40 dalit families also left the village.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scroll.in/article/828484/in-mirchpur-murderous-caste-violence-returns-to-haunt-a-haryana-village-after-seven-years|title=In Mirchpur, murderous caste violence returns to haunt a Haryana village after seven years|last=Dey|first=Abhishek|work=Scroll.in|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> On 24 August 2018, in a landmark judgement<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hrln.org/hrln/dalit-rights/pils-a-cases/757-mirchpur-case-a-landmark-judgement-for-dalit.html|title=Mirchpur Case: A Landmark Judgement for Dalit|last=Administrator|first=HRLN|website=www.hrln.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> [[Delhi High Court]] reversed the acquittal of 20 accused and upheld the conviction of 13 others in the case with enhanced punishment for nine of them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/mirchpur-dalit-killings-delhi-hc-says-planned-attack-by-jats-5322626/|title=Delhi HC convicts 20 fir Mirchpur Dalit killings: ‘Grim reminder of absence of equality, fraternity in society’|date=2018-08-24|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oneindia.com/india/deliberate-act-to-teach-dalits-a-lesson-says-hc-on-mirchpur-incident-2762923.html|title=Deliberate act to teach Dalits a lesson says HC on Mirchpur incident|work=One India|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en}}</ref> A bench of justices S Muralidhar and I S Mehta observed {{quote|The incidents of April 21, 2010 constituted an act of deliberate targeting of Balmiki houses by Jats, setting them on fire in a pre-planned and carefully orchestrated manner. It was pursuant to a conspiracy by the Jats to ‘teach the Balmikis a lesson’.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/hc-reverses-acquittal-of-20-mirchpur-attack-accused/articleshow/65536934.cms|title=HC reverses acquittal of 20 Mirchpur attack accused - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref>}} The statement that atrocities by those belonging to dominant castes against Scheduled Castes have shown no sign of abating even after 71 years of Independence forms part of the 209-page judgement authored by Justice S Muralidhar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barandbench.com/atrocities-against-scheduled-castes-have-shown-no-sign-of-abating-delhi-hc-on-mirchpur-case/|title=Atrocities against SCs have shown no sign of abating, Delhi HC on Mirchpur case|last=Singh|first=Aditi|date=2018-08-24|work=Bar & Bench|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.livelaw.in/mirchpur-dalit-killings-atrocities-against-scs-by-dominant-castes-continue-despite-71-years-of-independence-delhi-hc-convicts-20-read-judgment/|title=Mirchpur Dalit Killings: "Atrocities Against SCs By Dominant Castes Continue Despite 71 Years Of Independence": Delhi HC Convicts 20 [Read Judgment] Live Law|date=2018-08-24|work=Live Law|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> After the verdict, two police companies were deployed in Mirchpur under the charge of duty magistrate and DSP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/gurgaon/duty-magistrate-2-police-companies-deployed-in-mirchpur/articleshow/65536686.cms|title=Duty magistrate, two police companies deployed in Mirchpur - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> The next day, witnesses in the case didn't step out for work fearing backlash of the verdict.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/gurgaon/mirchpur-day-after-court-verdict-witnesses-stay-home/articleshow/65549122.cms|title=Mirchpur: Day after court verdict, witnesses stay home - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref>

